04580nam a22007815i 9780228011613DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280116137 a10.1515/97802280116132doi  a(DE-B1597)654839  a(OCoLC)1276809559  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1997.H62bP39 2022 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/722231 aPayne, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aL'Homme blessé /cRobert Payne. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b33 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQueer Film Classics ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tSynopsis -- tCredits -- tIntroduction -- tMaking Queer Desire Visible -- tQueer Masters and Disciples -- tThe Lives of L’Homme blessé -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawn into the circuit of men cruising for sex in and around a train station, restless adolescent Henri begins a frenzied pursuit of a dangerously charismatic older man, with sometimes violent and ultimately tragic consequences. Premiering at Cannes in 1983, Patrice Chéreau’s L’Homme blessé (The Wounded Man) was one of France’s first major cinematic releases to depict homosexual desire and queer sexual cultures in an unapologetic and complex way. It is a film that continues to resonate to this day.L’Homme blessé generated controversy with its dark tone and its treatment of an adolescent’s obsessive homoerotic desire, as well as Chéreau’s denial that the film is about homosexuality. Robert Payne guides readers through the powerfully erotic underworld of L’Homme blessé, where the film sidesteps fixed identities and draws viewers into the ambiguous spaces of queer desire, and argues that its visual composition depicts queer ways of seeing and generates queer ways of feeling. A look into the production’s historical and cultural backdrop uncovers a behind-the-scenes story of power and desire between its two screenwriters and the presence of HIV/AIDS hovering ominously and inevitably off screen. Original interviews trace the lives of L’Homme blessé across three continents and three decades and measure the film’s enduring value beyond its prestigious debut.Payne cements L’Homme blessé in its rightful place within queer cultural history and introduces the film to a new generation of viewers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHomosexuality in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1980s.  aFrance.  aFrench.  aGuy Hocquenghem.  aHerve Guibert.  aJean Genet.  aMichel Foucault.  aPatrice Chereau.  aauteur.  acinema.  acruising.  adesire.  afilm.  ahomoeroticism.  ahomosexuality.  ainfrastructure.  aqueer.  areception.  arepresentation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801161340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228011613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228011613/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles